base  filter, if it\u2019s not already selected. The Entity we created for this example will be listed: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1b3f011178df97730ec6fec7b4cbb2e15e73e689.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a Deployment Script Generator tool, specifically highlighting options related to database entities and fields. In the filter section, the option \u0022Missing in Database\u0022 is selected. The main area lists types and names, with a notable entry labeled \u0022Database Entity\u0022 for \u0022Project\u0022 emphasized in red. Below it, three \u0022Database Field\u0022 entries are shown: \u0022BusinessPartnerLookup.AvatarFilename,\u0022 \u0022BusinessPartnerLookup.AvatarFile,\u0022 and \u0022BusinessPartnerLookup.refLanguageId.\u0022 The database type is indicated as \u0022MsSql - Primary\u0022 in a dropdown menu. The overall purpose appears to be generating deployment scripts for missing database components.\n\n\n  \n Now, let\u2019s take a look at the script it generates. Select your entity and click the  Preview  button: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/cc0a54b01ca385fe980ee371c9e2e0b74a321b58.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for the \u0022Deployment Script Generator\u0022 within an application. The \u0022Options\u0022 section features a filter labeled \u0022Missing in Database\u0022 with a checkbox for \u0022Database Entity\u0022 selected. Below this, the \u0022Deployment Script\u0022 section includes dropdown menus for \u0022Database Type\u0022 set to \u0022MsSql - Primary\u0022 and \u0022Version\u0022 indicated as \u00221.0.0 (Current).\u0022 An \u0022Add to Deployment\u0022 button is also present. The \u0022Source Code\u0022 section contains a prominent \u0022Preview\u0022 button highlighted in red, suggesting the functionality to review the generated script before deployment. The overall purpose of this interface is to configure and generate scripts for deploying database entities.\n\n\n  \n Afterward, you will see the SQL script generated by the Generator in the right bar: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/31b1ac5479de5b9f7797358b55f1a25d866d38a4.png]\nDescription: The image displays a SQL script for creating and altering a database table named \u0022Projects.\u0022 In the script, the \u0060CREATE TABLE\u0060 statement defines the structure of the table with various columns, including \u0060[Name]\u0060, \u0060[Description]\u0060, \u0060[Start]\u0060, \u0060[End]\u0060, and others, all specified with their respective data types such as \u0060NVarChar(100)\u0060 and \u0060DateTime\u0060. Additionally, the \u0060ALTER TABLE\u0060 statement adds a foreign key constraint named \u0060FK_Project_Responsible\u0060 which references the \u0060Responsible_Id\u0060 from the \u0022BusinessPartner\u0022 table. The script\u0027s purpose is to define the schema for project management within a database context.\n\n\n  \n The first part of the script creates a new database table and fields for it, including both user-generated fields like  Name  and  Description  as well as default fields like  Id  or  RecordCreated . \n The second part (ALTER TABLE) defines a Foreign Key for one of the fields in the Entity. \n   Script Deployment \n You can either edit the script or execute it as-is. To execute it, select the script and click the  Add to Deployment  button. \n In the next step, confirm that you want to add the items to the search results, as we need to review them: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8fef26dd395460044c4a62465817544d1f978547.png]\nDescription: Dialog box titled \u0022Deployment Script\u0022 displaying a message indicating that the deployment script was updated successfully. The text prompts the user with the question: \u0022Do you want to put the generated items to the search results?\u0022 Below the message are two buttons labeled \u0022Yes\u0022 and \u0022No,\u0022 allowing the user to confirm or decline the action. The apparent purpose of this dialog is to seek user input regarding the inclusion of newly generated items in search results after a successful update.\n\n\n  \n By doing this, the generated scripts will appear in the  Found Results  tab in the right bar: \n   \n Double-click on one of the items, and you will be directed to the Deployment section of the Model Browser, where you can see your new deployment scripts at the end of the list, alongside all previously created scripts: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/142f467a8c0c1acd93eee481a4676beeac4c1de5.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:52:53"},"vector":[-0.029022096,-0.029279599,-0.06179679,0.047352556,0.004025766,-0.03742042,0.009976517,-0.020025967,0.0030943654,0.0073827296,0.0051068226,-0.008244781,-0.030105684,0.004810548,-0.00234039,0.015539014,-0.0011589761,-0.0088340305,0.038461953,0.054838788,-0.023604222,-0.05257003,0.06765674,0.0022260053,0.0103095705,0.022883654,-0.0088030975,-0.01591376,0.00093084783,-0.0015368784,0.022936499,-0.061107647,0.006324442,-0.03231488,0.015476873,-0.015194239,0.0010719603,0.01788258,-0.030231245,0.029343238,-0.00993826,0.02913635,-0.01706457,-0.010664835,0.016782992,-0.026134672,-0.026611099,-0.007592673,0.027658548,-0.015242814,-0.06037773,0.0037978205,0.034025542,-0.02915295,0.087070875,0.027547795,-0.06403702,0.019759057,-0.07363398,0.014938717,-0.011774045,0.0016132757,-0.002130906,-0.019520452,0.019761134,0.0015921551,-0.024411613,-0.0106247375,-0.013712385,-0.053107373,-0.0065732733,0.058383282,-0.05395935,-0.011384086,-0.050309177,-0.006710098,0.043474603,-0.018662712,-0.022963004,0.02718867,-0.03233257,-0.006360176,-0.023231002,0.005743854,0.006745737,-0.0053797574,-0.019607797,0.05328624,0.018110946,0.0019738125,0.0066069243,-